'''Kelis Rogers-Mora''' ({{IPAc-en|k|ə|ˈ|l|iː|s}};<ref>She can be heard singing her name in the song "[[Blindfold Me]]"</ref> born August 21, 1979), known [[mononym]]ously as '''Kelis''', is an American singer and a professionally trained chef.  At age 14, she was admitted to New York's [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School of Music & Art and Performing Arts]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/kelis-17133874|title=Kelis - Biography|website=Biography.com|access-date=April 6, 2016|archive-date=April 19, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160419110941/http://www.biography.com/people/kelis-17133874|url-status=live}}</ref> where she learned to play the saxophone and won a spot in the Girls Choir of Harlem.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608004091/Kelis.html|title=Kelis Biography|website=Musicianguide.com|access-date=May 29, 2017|archive-date=July 4, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704205547/https://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608004091/Kelis.html|url-status=live}}</ref> After she graduated from high school in 1997, Kelis took on a variety of jobs before landing a backup vocal slot on an album track called "Fairytalez", released by the American hip hop group [[Gravediggaz]]. She then began working with music producers [[Pharrell Williams]] and [[Chad Hugo]], known as [[The Neptunes]], which ultimately resulted in her being signed to [[Virgin Records]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/music-popular-and-jazz-biographies/kelis|title=Kelis {{!}} Encyclopedia.com|website=Encyclopedia.com|access-date=January 4, 2015|archive-date=May 2, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190502105244/https://www.encyclopedia.com/people/literature-and-arts/music-popular-and-jazz-biographies/kelis|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wearemitu.com/entertainment/milkshake-chef-kelis-facts/|title=Here Is A Little Bit About Kelis And Her Life Since Divorcing Nas And Living Her Best Life|last=danielli|date=February 27, 2019|website=Wearemitu.com|access-date=February 2, 2018|archive-date=February 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190228115444/https://wearemitu.com/entertainment/milkshake-chef-kelis-facts/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Kelis released her debut studio album ''[[Kaleidoscope (Kelis album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' with Virgin Records on December 7, 1999. Inspired by jazz and disco music from the 1970s, the album was a critical and international success.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theboombox.com/best-songs-from-kelis-kaleidoscope-album/|title=Five Best Songs From Kelis' 'Kaleidoscope' Album|last=Preezy|website=The Boombox|language=en|access-date=May 10, 2016|archive-date=September 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930061254/http://theboombox.com/best-songs-from-kelis-kaleidoscope-album/|url-status=live}}</ref> It spawned three singles: "[[Caught Out There]]", "[[Good Stuff (Kelis song)|Good Stuff]]", and "[[Get Along With You]]". The album reached number 43 in the United Kingdom while also becoming her first album to be certified gold.<ref name="BPI">{{cite web|url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/brit-certified/|title="British album certifications – Kelis – Kaleidoscope".|publisher=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|access-date=May 2, 2019|archive-date=April 7, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407115905/https://www.bpi.co.uk/brit-certified/|url-status=live}}</ref> She left her label [[Virgin Records]] after its follow-up ''[[Wanderland]]'' (2001) received little sales attention and no U.S. release until 2019. In 2003, Kelis released her third studio album ''[[Tasty (Kelis album)|Tasty]]''. The album produced the singles "[[Milkshake (song)|Milkshake]]", "[[Trick Me]]", "[[Millionaire (Kelis song)|Millionaire]]" (featuring [[André 3000]]), and "[[In Public]]" (featuring [[Nas]]). The album earned the singer commercial prominence. Her fourth album, ''[[Kelis Was Here]]'' (2006), was preceded by the lead single "[[Bossy (Kelis song)|Bossy]]" (featuring [[Too Short]]) and reached number 10 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]. Kelis took a hiatus from music after its release, venturing into culinary arts at [[Le Cordon Bleu]]. She later signed with [[will.i.am Music Group|will.i.am]] and began recording her fifth album, ''[[Flesh Tone]]'', which was released in 2010. The album spawned four singles, including "[[Acapella (Kelis song)|Acapella]]" and "[[4th of July (Fireworks)]]", which were successful on the US [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] chart and the [[UK Dance Chart|UK Dance Singles Chart]]. Kelis' [[neo soul]]-inspired sixth studio album ''[[Food (Kelis album)|Food]]'' (2014) became her second top-twenty album in the UK and spawned three singles: "[[Jerk Ribs]]", "[[Rumble (Kelis song)|Rumble]]" and "Friday Fish Fry".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/jerk-ribs-ep/id821695087 |title=Jerk Ribs – EP by Kelis |website=[[iTunes Store]] (US) |date=February 18, 2014 |access-date=June 13, 2016 |archive-date=September 21, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921212228/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/jerk-ribs-ep/id821695087 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/ie/album/rumble-ep/id836016714 |title=Rumble – EP by Kelis |website=iTunes Store (Ireland) |access-date=June 13, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726225052/https://itunes.apple.com/ie/album/rumble-ep/id836016714 |archive-date=July 26, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/friday-fish-fry-ep/id886752279 |title=Friday Fish Fry – EP by Kelis |website=iTunes Store (US) |date=July 15, 2014 |access-date=June 13, 2016 |archive-date=June 12, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160612001207/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/friday-fish-fry-ep/id886752279 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Kelis has been recognized at the [[Brit Awards]], [[Q Awards]], [[NME Awards]], and [[Grammy Award]]s ceremonies.<ref name=":0">Kate Hutchinson, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/mar/01/kelis-food-david-sitek-ninja-tune 'Soul Food'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126074658/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/mar/01/kelis-food-david-sitek-ninja-tune |date=January 26, 2017 }}, ''The T Dawg '', March 1, 2014.</ref> Her musical output, both as a lead and featured artist, encompasses various genres. She has collaborated with R&B and hip hop acts including [[Busta Rhymes]] and [[Clipse]]; electronic and dance producers such as [[Calvin Harris]], [[Timo Maas]], and [[Richard X]]; pop and rock acts [[Enrique Iglesias]] and [[No Doubt]]; and indie and alternative musicians including [[Björk]] and [[Dave Sitek]]. She has sold six million records worldwide<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/kelis/kelis-all-hearts-tour-interview|title=Kelis Interview - Contactmusic.com|work=Contactmusic.com|date=October 27, 2010|access-date=April 18, 2015|archive-date=April 19, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419040229/http://www.contactmusic.com/kelis/kelis-all-hearts-tour-interview|url-status=live}}</ref> and has had particular success in the United Kingdom, where ten of her singles have peaked within the top ten of the [[UK Singles Chart]].

==Early life==
Kelis Rogers was born and raised in the [[Frederick Douglass Houses]] in the [[Harlem]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]]. Her first name is a [[portmanteau]] of her father's name, Kenneth (1944–2000) and her mother's name, Eveliss. Her father Kenneth was an [[African Americans|African-American]] [[jazz]] musician and  [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] [[minister of religion|minister]] and was formerly a professor at [[Wesleyan University]].<!-- what years? --><ref name="guardian">{{cite web |last=Pool |first=Hannah |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/feb/01/urbanmusic.questiontime |title=Question time: Kelis |work=The Guardian |date=February 1, 2007 |access-date=March 5, 2007 |archive-date=February 4, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204035529/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/feb/01/urbanmusic.questiontime |url-status=live }}</ref> Her mother Eveliss is a [[Chinese Americans|Chinese]]-[[Puerto Ricans in the United States|Puerto Rican]] fashion designer who inspired Kelis to pursue her singing career. She has three sisters, Kelis being the third-born of the four girls.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/kelis |title=Kelis |publisher=[[MTV (UK and Ireland)|MTV UK]]. [[MTV Networks Europe]] |access-date=February 27, 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110904003131/http://www.mtv.co.uk/artists/kelis |archive-date=September 4, 2011  }}</ref>

As a child, Kelis sang in church [[choir]]s and played violin, piano, and saxophone while attending [[Manhattan Country School]], a private school. At the age of 13, Kelis shaved off all of her hair. In an interview with [[Charlotte Roche]], Kelis says she was kicked out of her parents' house at the age of sixteen for bad behavior, stating that she would sometimes clash with her mother,<ref name="guardian"/> but continued her education at the [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School of Music & Art and Performing Arts]], where she formed the R&B trio BLU (Black Ladies United). Kelis was also a bartender and a sales associate at a clothing store before graduating high school.

==Career==
===1997–2002: ''Kaleidoscope'' and ''Wanderland''===
In 1997, Kelis provided background vocals on "Fairytalez", a track on hip hop group [[Gravediggaz]]' album ''[[The Pick, the Sickle and the Shovel]]''. Afterwards, a friend introduced Kelis to [[The Neptunes]] ([[Pharrell Williams]] and [[Chad Hugo]]); they formed a strong bond, and with their support she landed a record deal with [[Virgin Records]]. According to Kelis, Virgin Records advised her that publishing royalties would be split evenly between Williams, Hugo, and herself, but this turned out not to be the case; Kelis made no money from sales of her first two albums on the label.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/pa7nyk/kelis-interview-kaleidoscope-pharrell-nerd-2019 | title=Kelis on 20 years of staying ahead of the game | date=November 22, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/jan/30/unmasked-singer-kelis-on-music-men-and-her-missing-money | title=Unmasked singer: Kelis on music, men and her missing money | website=[[TheGuardian.com]] | date=January 30, 2020 }}</ref> Kelis has also said that Williams was credited as a songwriter on songs of hers that he had not written.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/beyonce-updates-renaissance-to-remove-reportedly-unauthorised-kelis-sample-3282055 | title=Beyoncé updates 'Renaissance' to remove reportedly unauthorised Kelis sample | website=[[NME]] | date=August 3, 2022 }}</ref>

Kelis began recording her debut album, ''[[Kaleidoscope (Kelis album)|Kaleidoscope]]'', in mid-1998 and was finished within a year.{{citation needed|date=August 2022}} Produced by The Neptunes and released by Virgin Records in 1999, ''Kaleidoscope'' peaked at number 144 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and reached the top five on the [[Top Heatseekers]] chart.<ref name=Billboard>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/artist/305667/kelis/chart|title=Kelis|work=billboard.com|access-date=April 21, 2020|archive-date=April 1, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401143946/https://www.billboard.com/artist/305667/kelis/chart|url-status=live}}</ref> As of 2006, the album has sold 249,000 copies, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref>{{cite magazine | last = Caulfield | first = Keith | title = Ask Billboard | magazine = Billboard | publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc. | date = November 2, 2006 | url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/56764/ask-billboard | access-date = June 4, 2008 | archive-date = September 22, 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140922022614/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/56764/ask-billboard | url-status = live }}</ref> Its lead and most notable single, "[[Caught Out There]]", became a top ten [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] hit and peaked at number 54 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=Billboard/> During this time, Kelis featured on [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]]'s U.S. top 40 single, "[[Got Your Money]]".

The album performed better in Europe, where "Caught Out There" was a moderate hit in most European countries except the United Kingdom, where the song saw massive success, peaking at number four on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. A second single, "[[Good Stuff (Kelis song)|Good Stuff]]" (featuring [[Pusha T|Terrar]] of [[Clipse]]), reached number 19; the third, "[[Get Along with You]]", was less successful, reaching number 51.<ref name=officialcharts>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/8721/KELIS/|title=KELIS|work=officialcharts.com|access-date=May 28, 2015|archive-date=June 12, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612104021/http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/8721/kelis/|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[British Phonographic Industry]] certified ''Kaleidoscope'' gold for sales of 100,000 copies in the United Kingdom,<ref name="bpi-kaleidoscope">{{cite web| title = KELIS, KALEIDOSCOPE, Gold | work = [[British Phonographic Industry]] | date = March 2, 2001 | url = http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=29467 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180103072654/https://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=29467 | url-status = dead | archive-date = January 3, 2018 | access-date =June 4, 2008}}</ref> where it reached number 43 on the [[UK Albums Chart]].

In 2001, Kelis won the [[Brit Awards|Brit Award]] for International Breakthrough Act and the [[NME Awards|''NME'' Award]] for Best R&B/Soul Act before joining [[Moby]] and [[U2]] on their [[Area Festival|Area:One]] and [[Elevation Tour|Elevation]] tours, respectively. Kelis and the Neptunes' output at this time was heralded as foreshadowing an innovation in [[contemporary R&B]], but she later said, "I was never an R&B artist. People coined me one but that's because, especially if you're in the States, if you're black and you sing, then you're R&B".<ref name=":0"/> Her colorful style in both clothing and hair received considerable attention.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Dirshe |first1=Siraad |title=Happy Birthday, Kelis! A Look Back At Her Most Iconic Hairstyles |url=https://www.essence.com/hair/kelis-hair/ |magazine=[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]] |date=August 21, 2018 |access-date=April 12, 2019 |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412123711/https://www.essence.com/hair/kelis-hair/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Kelis's second album ''[[Wanderland]]'' was released in 2001 in Europe, Asia, and Latin America but did not receive a North American release until 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/06/05/kelis-neptunes-produced-record-wanderland-is-finally-streaming |title=Kelis' Neptunes-produced record Wanderland is finally streaming |publisher=The Fader |date=2019-06-05 |accessdate=2022-08-03}}</ref> According to Kelis, her U.S. record company at the time, [[Virgin Records|Virgin]], had laid off those that worked on ''Kaleidoscope''; their replacements did not understand or believe in ''Wanderland''. Eventually, Kelis was dropped from Virgin in America around the time of the album's European release, though she remained on the label's roster in Europe.<ref name=selftitled>{{cite web|url=http://www.self-titledmag.com/2014/04/21/interview-kelis-explains-how-she-spent-17-years-being-consistently-inconsistent|title=INTERVIEW: Kelis On... EDM's Early Days, Pop Artistry and the Importance of Never, Ever Looking Back|work=self-titledmag.com|access-date=January 1, 2015|archive-date=March 13, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150313194559/http://www.self-titledmag.com/2014/04/21/interview-kelis-explains-how-she-spent-17-years-being-consistently-inconsistent/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="mp3-apr06">{{cite web|last=Rolls|first=Chris|title=Exclusive Interview with Kelis|work=MP3.com|publisher=CNET Networks, Inc.|date=April 24, 2006|url=http://www.mp3.com/features/stories/4233.html|access-date=June 4, 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323221445/http://www.mp3.com/features/stories/4233.html|archive-date=March 23, 2009}}</ref> A commercial failure, ''Wanderland'' peaked at number 78 in the UK; its sole single release, "[[Young, Fresh n' New]]", managed to crack the top forty on the UK Singles Chart.<ref name=Eye>{{cite web|url=http://www.eye.net/eye/issue/issue_02.19.04/beat/kelis.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060630043342/http://www.eye.net/eye/issue/issue_02.19.04/beat/kelis.html|title=Kelis|archive-date=June 30, 2006|work=eye.net}}</ref><ref name=officialcharts/> The album, which was produced in its entirety by the Neptunes and features collaborations with members of Clipse and [[No Doubt]], received a subdued critical response.<ref name=Independent-20040506/> ''[[NME]]'' wrote: "In our collective fantasies, Kelis Rogers is already the ghetto-fabulous sex-queen of discodelic future-funk pop-rock-soul [...] But beyond the initial shopping-and-funking dazzle, there is way too much filler here for a hotly hyped alterna-soul princess with her eyes on the big prize".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/5756|title=NME Reviews|date=September 12, 2005|work=nme.com|access-date=April 21, 2020|archive-date=March 4, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113930/http://www.nme.com/reviews/5756|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The Fader]]'' later referred to ''Wanderland'' as "Kelis’s long lost masterpiece".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/11/13/introducing-kelis-week |title=Introducing The FADER’s Kelis Week |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref>

In 2002, Kelis recorded "So Be It" for the [[Red Hot Organization]]'s [[Fela Kuti]] tribute CD, ''[[Red Hot and Riot]]'', from which all proceeds were donated to AIDS awareness charities. The same year she had a top 20 US club hit with a remix of "Young, Fresh 'n' New", produced by [[Timo Maas]], who subsequently featured Kelis on his single, "Help Me".<ref name=Billboard/><ref name=officialcharts/> She hosted the DanceStar USA Awards ceremony at that year's [[Winter Music Conference]].<ref name=Eye/>

===2003–2005: ''Tasty''===
In 2003, Kelis achieved a second top ten hit in the UK as a featured artist on [[Richard X]]'s "[[Finest Dreams]]", a reworking of [[the S.O.S. Band]]'s 1986 single "The Finest", and a European club hit (and UK top 40 single) as a featured artist on "[[Let's Get Ill]]" by [[P. Diddy]], her manager for a brief period.<ref name="thefader-20171115"/><ref name=officialcharts/><ref name="bluesandsoul"/> She found mainstream success in the U.S. later in 2003 with her [[Hot Dance Club Play]] number one, ''Billboard'' Hot 100 top three single "[[Milkshake (song)|Milkshake]]"; this helped to propel her third album ''[[Tasty (Kelis album)|Tasty]]'' to gold status in the U.S., where it peaked at number 27 on the ''Billboard'' 200 and has sold 533,000 copies, according to Nielsen SoundScan.<ref name=Billboard/><ref name="riaa"/><ref name="billboard-oct07">{{Cite magazine|first=Hillary|last=Crosley|title=Report: Kelis Splits With Jive|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047589/report-kelis-splits-with-jive|magazine=Billboard|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|date=October 29, 2007|access-date=June 4, 2008|archive-date=September 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904062618/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1047589/report-kelis-splits-with-jive|url-status=live}}</ref> "Milkshake" also went gold, selling over 500,000 copies,<ref name="riaa">{{cite web|title=Gold and Platinum – Searchable Database|work=RIAA.com|url=https://www.riaa.comgoldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH|access-date=June 4, 2008|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH|archive-date=June 26, 2007}}</ref> and earned Kelis a [[Grammy Award]] nomination in [[46th Grammy Awards|2004]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Urban/Alternative Performance|Best Urban/Alternative Performance]].<ref name=Grammy />

Although the Neptunes contributed several tracks to ''Tasty''&mdash;the album was released by their label [[Star Trak Entertainment]], a joint venture with [[Arista Records]]&mdash;Kelis also collaborated with other producers such as [[Dallas Austin]], [[André 3000]], [[Rockwilder]], and [[Raphael Saadiq]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2004/02/21/kelis-interview |title=Kelis Interview |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref><ref name=Independent-20040506>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/kelis-the-comeback-kid-59233.html|title=Kelis: The comeback kid|work=The Independent|date=May 6, 2004|access-date=September 2, 2017|archive-date=March 6, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180306144124/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/features/kelis-the-comeback-kid-59233.html|url-status=live}}</ref> She stated in an interview: "I felt like I had a lot to prove with this album. People had started messing with me along the lines of 'Is she REALLY any good without The Neptunes?' &mdash; which I knew was ridiculous. And so I was like, 'I'll take that challenge'."<ref name="bluesandsoul">{{cite web|url=http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/249/kelis_talks_milkshake_and_tasty_hits|title=Kelis Talks 'Milkshake' And 'Tasty' Hits|publisher=Bluesandsoul.com|access-date=December 14, 2012|archive-date=October 7, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007070858/http://www.bluesandsoul.com/feature/249/kelis_talks_milkshake_and_tasty_hits|url-status=live}}</ref> The album was well-received critically; ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that ''Tasty'' is "Kelis' past—big beats, out-there imagery, and sex appeal—refined [...] much of the beauty of ''Tasty'' is in witnessing Kelis rise to the challenge of working with multiple imaginative maestros."<ref name="TASTY by Kelis">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/tasty/kelis/critic-reviews |title=TASTY by Kelis |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/article/2003/12/12/tasty/ |title=Tasty |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref>

"Milkshake" and ''Tasty'' immediately found success in Europe. According to the BPI, ''Tasty'' went platinum in the United Kingdom, selling over 300,000 copies, and "Milkshake" went silver, selling over 200,000 units.<ref name="bpi-tasty">{{cite web|title=KELIS, TASTY, Platinum|work=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|date=October 22, 2004|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=31783|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323194420/http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=31783|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 23, 2009|access-date=June 4, 2008}}</ref><ref name="bpi-milkshake">{{cite web|title=KELIS, MILKSHAKE, Silver|work=[[British Phonographic Industry]]|date=February 13, 2004|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=31470|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090323194415/http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=31470|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 23, 2009|access-date=June 4, 2008}}</ref> The album's second single, the Dallas Austin-produced "[[Trick Me]]", went to the top ten in many European countries during mid-2004; it did not, however, garner success in the U.S. in the absence of promotion by [[Jive Records]], the label Kelis had been transferred to after Arista Records folded at the time of ''Tasty''{{'}}s release.<ref name="mp3-apr06"/> Kelis' success grew in Australia, where ''Tasty'' went gold and where "Milkshake" and "Trick Me" went platinum.{{fact|date=August 2022}} Kelis followed the success of the third ''Tasty'' single, the BPI silver-certified "[[Millionaire (Kelis song)|Millionaire]]" (featuring André 3000), with the Rockwilder-produced track "[[In Public]]" (featuring Nas), which reached number 17 on the UK chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/award/13948-4684-1 |title=10 of the best: Björk |access-date=2022-08-07}}</ref><ref name=officialcharts/>

"[[Not in Love (Enrique Iglesias song)|Not in Love]]", Kelis's collaboration with [[Enrique Iglesias]] from his 2003 album ''[[7 (Enrique Iglesias album)|7]]'', was released as a single the following year, reaching the UK top five.<ref name=officialcharts/> Although the single failed to chart on the U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100, it topped the country's Hot Dance Club Play chart.<ref>[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=Enrique Iglesias|chart=Dance Club Songs}}]</ref> Also in 2004, Kelis collaborated with [[Björk]] on a remix of the latter's track "[[Oceania (song)|Oceania]]" (from Björk's album ''[[Medúlla]]''), which appeared as a B-side to the Björk album's second single, "[[Who Is It (Björk song)|Who Is It]]".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/mar/26/10-of-the-best-bjork |title=Virgin - Kelis Ft Andre 3 - Millionaire |access-date=2022-08-07}}</ref> Kelis toured as the opening act for fellow Jive artist [[Britney Spears]]'s [[The Onyx Hotel Tour]]{{fact|date=August 2022}} before headlining her own tour of Australia and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ra.co/news/5282 |title=Missy cans European tour and Kelis Australian dates change |access-date=2022-08-07}}</ref> In 2005, she was featured on the soundtrack to the film ''[[Just Like Heaven (film)|Just Like Heaven]]'' with a [[cover version]] of [[The Pretenders]]' "[[Brass in Pocket]]" (1979).<ref>{{cite web |title=Just Like Heaven Soundtrack Music - Complete Song List |url=https://www.tunefind.com/movie/just-like-heaven |publisher=Tunefind.com |date=September 16, 2005 |access-date=April 12, 2019 |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412123236/https://www.tunefind.com/movie/just-like-heaven |url-status=live }}</ref>

===2006–2008: ''Kelis Was Here''===
Kelis contributed a track titled "80's Joint" to [[Step Up (Original Soundtrack)|the soundtrack]] of the 2006 dance film ''[[Step Up (film)|Step Up]]''. She collaborated with Busta Rhymes and will.i.am on the track "[[I Love My Bitch]]", the second single from Rhymes's 2006 album ''[[The Big Bang (Busta Rhymes album)|The Big Bang]]''. This was the second time Kelis collaborated with Rhymes, the first being his 2001 song "What It Is".

[[File:Kelis 1.jpg|thumb|Kelis performing during [[Manchester Pride]] in [[Manchester]], [[England]] on August 29, 2010]]
Kelis's fourth studio album, ''[[Kelis Was Here]]'', was released in 2006, and debuted and peaked at number ten on the ''Billboard'' 200. Despite the career-high debut, the album has sold only 157,000 copies in the United States as of 2007, according to Nielsen SoundScan.<ref name=Billboard/><ref name="billboard-oct07"/> In the UK, ''Kelis Was Here'' charted at number 41 and has sold 60,000 copies, earning a silver certification from the BPI.<ref name=officialcharts/><ref name="bpi-keliswashere">{{cite web|title=KELIS, KELIS WAS HERE, Silver |work=[[British Phonographic Industry]] |date=September 29, 2006 |url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=32684 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180103072620/https://www.bpi.co.uk/platinum/platinumright.asp?rq=search_plat&r_id=32684 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 3, 2018 |access-date=June 4, 2008 }}</ref> The album was Kelis's first not to feature contributions from The Neptunes, as she had left Star Trak by this time; instead, she recorded with [[Cee-Lo]], [[Max Martin]], [[Raphael Saadiq]], [[Scott Storch]], and [[will.i.am]], among others.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.out.com/entertainment/2006/05/16/kelis-gets-bossy |title=Kelis Gets Bossy |access-date=2022-08-04}}
</ref><ref name="mp3-apr06"/><ref name=MTV-20160822/> According to Kelis, she received no support from [[Jive Records]] for the recording or promotion of ''Kelis Was Here'' and argued heavily with the label, later describing the period as "[not] the most creative atmosphere" and "the only time where I felt like I was being pulled in different directions. There were too many cooks in the kitchen".<ref name=selftitled/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vibe.com/music/music-news/long-convo-kelis-49135/ |title=A Long Convo With… Kelis |access-date=2022-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://gal-dem.com/kelis-interview-midnight-snacks/ |title=‘Am I going to die if people don’t like my work?’ Kelis on getting comfortable with herself |access-date=2022-08-03}}</ref> [[MTV]] characterised critical consensus of the album as "intriguingly intelligent, if unjustifiably disjointed and long" and wrote in 2016 that "it remains her most creatively anarchic project".<ref name=MTV-20160822>{{cite web |url=https://www.mtv.com/news/nxvpzr/kelis-was-here-10-years-later |title='Kelis Was Here', 10 Years Later |access-date=2022-08-03}}</ref> ''Kelis Was Here'' was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary R&B Album|Best Contemporary R&B Album]] at the [[49th Grammy Awards|2007 Grammy Awards]].<ref name=Grammy>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/kelis|title=Kelis|date=2019-02-15|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>

''Kelis Was Here''{{'}}s lead single, "[[Bossy (Kelis song)|Bossy]]" (featuring [[Too Short]]), was a moderate hit in the U.S., peaking at number 16; it additionally went multi-platinum as a mobile phone [[ringtone]], according to the RIAA.<ref name=Billboard/><ref name="riaa"/> The second U.S. single, "[[Blindfold Me]]" (featuring Nas), reached number 91 on the R&B chart and did not chart on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.<ref name=Billboard/> Kelis's European label, Virgin, instead released the Cee-Lo-featuring "[[Lil Star]]", which was another top ten hit for Kelis in the United Kingdom (peaking at number three on the [[UK Singles Chart]]).<ref name=officialcharts/> During mid 2007, Kelis toured in Europe, appearing in numerous festivals across the United Kingdom, France, and Germany, such as [[Wireless Festival|Wireless]], [[Rise Festival|Rise]] and [[Gurtenfestival]].{{citation needed|date=August 2022}} [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] chose Kelis to help advertise the 2007 [[Ford Edge]], and she recorded a theme song for the commercial, titled "Push It to the Edge", with help from producer Scott Storch.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecarconnection.com/Auto_News/Daily_Auto_News/Ford_Chooses_Kelis_To_Push_Edge.S173.A11606.html |title=Ford Chooses Kelis To Push Edge |access-date=January 9, 2007 |work=TheCarConnection.com |date=December 19, 2006 |archive-date=September 27, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927193536/http://www.thecarconnection.com/Auto_News/Daily_Auto_News/Ford_Chooses_Kelis_To_Push_Edge.S173.A11606.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Jive Records dropped Kelis in late 2007.<ref name="ew-oct07"/> Her manager at the time said that the singer was working with Cee-Lo Green on an [[alternative dance]] album and would be shopping a pop album produced by songwriter [[Guy Chambers]].<ref name="ew-oct07"/> Scottish [[electronica]] producer [[Calvin Harris]] was also said to be collaborating with her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pr-inside.com/entertainment-blog/2007/05/14/kelis-to-work-with-calvin-harris/ |title=Kelis To Work With Calvin Harris? |access-date=November 25, 2007 |work=PR-inside.com |date=May 14, 2007 |archive-url = https://archive.today/20080203193648/http://www.pr-inside.com/entertainment-blog/2007/05/14/kelis-to-work-with-calvin-harris/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archive-date = February 3, 2008}}</ref> Kelis subsequently took a hiatus from music: "I was like, 'I will never put out another record again, I hate this business, I hate all these people.' I was in this race that I didn't even realise that I was in. I woke up and ten years had passed. That was never my plan".<ref name=":0" />

After Kelis left Jive, the label released a fourteen-track greatest hits album titled ''[[The Hits (Kelis album)|The Hits]]'' in 2008. The album does not contain any previously unreleased songs; [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]]'s "[[Got Your Money]]", [[N.E.R.D]]'s "Truth or Dare", and [[Richard X]]'s "Finest Dreams" appear on the album alongside every charted Kelis single to that date, with the exception of "Blindfold Me". Also in 2008, the ''Kelis Was Here'' album track "[[I Don't Think So]]" became a top 40 hit in Australia after being used in promotion for the [[Big Brother Australia 2008|2008 season]] of the reality series ''[[Big Brother Australia]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Chris |last=Pycroft |title=Kelis out of the charts? I don't think so! |url=http://music.generationq.net/bm/news/kelis-returns-to-charts-001.shtml |work=GenQ |date=April 27, 2008 |access-date=June 4, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502164642/http://music.generationq.net/bm/news/kelis-returns-to-charts-001.shtml |archive-date=May 2, 2008  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/tv-unlikely-saviour-of-songs-lost-in-the-static-20080712-gdslt5.html |title=TV, unlikely saviour of songs lost in the static |access-date=2022-08-03}}</ref>

===2009–2011: ''Flesh Tone''===
In 2009, Kelis signed to [[Interscope Records]] via the [[will.i.am Music Group]] to release her fifth studio album, ''[[Flesh Tone]]'', which included production from [[Ammo (musician)|Ammo]], [[Jean Baptiste Kouame|Free School]], [[Benny Benassi]], [[Burns (musician)|Burns]], [[Boys Noize]], [[Benny Benassi]], [[DJ Tocadisco]], [[will.i.am]], and [[David Guetta]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Mariel |last=Concepcion |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/music-news/exclusive-kelis-signs-to-william-music-groupinterscope-266542/ |title=Exclusive: Kelis Signs To will.i.am Music Group/Interscope |work=Billboard |date=2019-09-03 |accessdate=2022-08-03}}</ref><ref name=idolator>{{cite web | url=https://www.idolator.com/5322931/kelis-the-idolator-interview?chrome=1 | title=The Idolator Interview: Kelis | date=December 14, 2009 }}</ref><ref name="thefader-20171115">{{cite web | url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/11/15/kelis-flesh-tone-album | title=Kelis's Flesh Tone is peak pop, and it deserves more credit }}</ref> ''Flesh Tone'' marked Kelis' transition into [[dance music|dance]] music. Kelis said she was hesitant to sign to another major label after her experiences with Jive Records but did not want the album to be "swept under the rug with a smaller label".<ref name=idolator/> Coinciding with her change in musical direction, Kelis appeared on [[Basement Jaxx]]'s 2009 album ''[[Scars (Basement Jaxx album)|Scars]]'' on the title track, on Benassi's 2010 single "Spaceship" (with [[apl.de.ap]] and [[Jean Baptiste Kouame|Jean Baptiste]])&mdash;a top 40 U.S. and UK club hit<ref name=Billboard/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/dance-singles-chart/20100822/104/ | title=Official Dance Singles Chart Top 40 &#124; Official Charts Company | website=[[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]] }}</ref>&mdash;and on the [[Crookers]] single "No Security" from their debut album ''[[Tons of Friends (Crookers album)|Tons of Friends]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/r1811246 |title=Tons of Friends - Crookers : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=AllMusic |access-date=December 14, 2012 |archive-date=May 6, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506145306/https://www.allmusic.com/album/tons-of-friends-mw0001978164 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Jeffries |first=David |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/r1633979 |title=Scars - Basement Jaxx : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards |website=AllMusic |date=September 22, 2009 |access-date=December 14, 2012 |archive-date=May 6, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506145307/https://www.allmusic.com/album/scars-mw0000824409 |url-status=live }}</ref>

Critical reception to ''Flesh Tone'' was generally positive, with [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]] naming the album Kelis's best since her debut, ''Kaleidoscope''.<ref name="TASTY by Kelis"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14439-flesh-tone/ |title=ALBUMS - Flesh Tone - Kelis - 2010 |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref> The first single from ''Flesh Tone'', "[[Acapella (Kelis song)|Acapella]]" (produced by David Guetta), debuted in the top five on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and reached number one on the U.S. [[Hot Dance Club Songs]] and the UK Dance Chart, eventually receiving a BPI silver certification.<ref name=officialcharts/><ref name=Billboard/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/dance-singles-chart/20100418/104/ | title=Official Dance Singles Chart Top 40 &#124; Official Charts Company | website=[[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/award/10793-1939-1 |title=Polydor - Kelis - Acapella |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref> ''Flesh Tone'' peaked at number 48 on the ''Billboard'' 200 and at number five on the [[Dance/Electronic Albums]].<ref name=Billboard/> The second single, "[[4th of July (Fireworks)]]", was accompanied by a video co-directed by Kelis herself (with [[Rankin (photographer)|Rankin]] and [[Nicole Ehrlich]]) and became a top ten club hit in America and Britain.<ref name=Billboard/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/dance-singles-chart/20100711/104/ | title=Official Dance Singles Chart Top 40 &#124; Official Charts Company | website=[[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]] }}</ref> Subsequent singles, "[[Scream (Kelis song)|Scream]]" and "[[Brave (Kelis song)|Brave]]", made minimal chart impact.

During mid-2010 Kelis embarked on her first U.S. tour, titled [[All Hearts]] with [[Robyn]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Becky |last=Bain |url=http://idolator.com/5523492/kelis-and-robyn-tour-dates-all-hearts |title=Kelis And Robyn Announce Dates For All Hearts Tour &#124; Music News, Reviews, and Gossip on |publisher=Idolator.com |date=June 1, 2010 |access-date=December 14, 2012 |archive-date=July 28, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100728172953/http://idolator.com/5523492/kelis-and-robyn-tour-dates-all-hearts |url-status=live }}</ref> amid a selection of club, festival, and solo dates that continued through 2011 – these included [[Glastonbury Festival 2010|Glastonbury]], [[The Big Chill (music festival)|The Big Chill]], Good Vibrations Festival, and [[Lovebox Festival|Lovebox]]. Kelis appears on the [[Mark Ronson]]-produced track "The Man Who Stole a Leopard" from the 2010 [[Duran Duran]] album ''[[All You Need Is Now]]'', a song she and the band performed in a concert directed by filmmaker [[David Lynch]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/duran-duran-and-david-lynch-collaborate-on-spectacular-l-a-concert-247968/ |title=Duran Duran and David Lynch Collaborate on Spectacular L.A. Concert |access-date=2022-08-07}}</ref> She co-wrote the song "Waiting" for British pop singer [[Cheryl Cole]]'s ''[[Messy Little Raindrops]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.starobserver.com.au/news/cheryl-cole-messy-little-raindrops/38728 |title=CHERYL COLE – MESSY LITTLE RAINDROPS |access-date=2022-08-07}}</ref> Kelis then collaborated with Scottish producer [[Calvin Harris]] on the 2011 single "[[Bounce (Calvin Harris song)|Bounce]]", the lead single from Harris' third studio album, ''[[18 Months]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cragg|first=Michael|title=New music: Calvin Harris featuring Kelis – Bounce {{!}} Music|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2011/may/02/new-music-calvin-harris-kelis-bounce|work=The Guardian|access-date=June 19, 2011|date=May 2, 2011|location=London|archive-date=October 27, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027003653/http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2011/may/02/new-music-calvin-harris-kelis-bounce|url-status=live}}</ref> "Bounce" debuted at number two on the [[UK Singles Chart]], becoming Kelis's tenth UK top ten single and her biggest selling in the country (as of 2017).<ref name=officialcharts/><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/keliss-official-top-20-biggest-selling-singles-revealed__20000/ | title=Kelis's Official Top 20 biggest selling singles | website=[[Official Charts Company|Official Charts]] }}</ref> It eventually received a platinum certification from the BPI.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bpi.co.uk/award/1029-3376-1 | title=Award }}</ref>

===2012–2017: ''Food''===
[[File:Palmesus 2011 - Kelis.jpg|thumb|Kelis on stage in 2011]]
In 2012, Kelis's management firm at the time announced that her sixth studio album would be released in late 2012 and feature production from [[Skream]], [[Burns (DJ)|BURNS]], Tom Neville, [[Dan Black]], and [[Caspa]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://atlantablackstar.com/2012/05/20/kelis-to-release-new-album-later-this-year/ | title=Kelis to Release New Album Later This Year | date=May 21, 2012 }}</ref> The first single, the Skream-produced "Distance", received its UK radio premiere in mid 2012.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/482214/kelis-goes-the-distance-with-skream-produced-single-listen |title=Kelis Goes the 'Distance' with Skream-Produced Single: Listen - The Juice |magazine=Billboard |access-date=December 14, 2012 |archive-date=January 31, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130131064046/http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/482214/kelis-goes-the-distance-with-skream-produced-single-listen |url-status=live }}</ref> Kelis said of the album, "I've been on a real 1990s vibe with this record, it's kind of [[trip hop|trip-hoppish]] [...] it's more [[electro (music)|electro]], it's a little deeper and darker".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/kelis/64641 |title=Kelis unveils new track– listen &#124; News |publisher=Nme.Com |date=July 1, 2012 |access-date=December 14, 2012 |archive-date=May 4, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504163953/http://www.nme.com/news/kelis/64641 |url-status=live }}</ref> Kelis was featured on Dan Black's single "Hearts" and Skream's "Copy Cat" (both 2013), the latter of which led to a dispute after Kelis alleged that Skream refused to have her appear in the music video.<ref name=skream/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2013/05/23/dan-black-hearts-video/|title=Video Premiere: Dan Black Featuring Kelis, 'Hearts'|work=Buzzworthy|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150504072639/http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2013/05/23/dan-black-hearts-video/|archive-date=May 4, 2015}}</ref> She subsequently opted to move on from dance music: "when everyone else starts doing it, it's not as much fun [...] too much time went by. That [sound] wasn't a new idea any more".<ref name=guardian-mar14/> The rest of the material from these recording sessions remains unreleased.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soulbounce.com/2014/03/kelis-does-the-trick-at-bbc-radios-6-music-festival/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140320113135/http://www.soulbounce.com/soul/2014/03/kelis-does-the-trick-at-bbc-radios-6-music-festival/|url-status=dead|title=Kelis Does The 'Trick' At BBC Radio's 6 Music Festival &#124; SoulBounce &#124; SoulBounce|archive-date=March 20, 2014|website=Soulbounce.com}}</ref>

By 2013, Kelis was working with producer [[Dave Sitek]], and it was announced that she would release two albums via Sitek's label, Federal Prism.<ref name=skream>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a454743/kelis-rejected-by-skream-for-copy-cat-music-video.html |title=Kelis rejected by Skream for 'Copy Cat' music video - Music News |website=Digital Spy |date=January 29, 2013 |access-date=April 23, 2014 |archive-date=October 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014235240/http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a454743/kelis-rejected-by-skream-for-copy-cat-music-video.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2013/03/dave-sitek-federal-prism-2013-release-schedule/ |title=Dave Sitek's Label Stacks 2013 Releases With TV on the Radio, Scarlett Johansson, and More &#124; SPIN &#124; Music News |publisher=SPIN |date=March 11, 2013 |access-date=April 23, 2014 |archive-date=October 19, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019111347/http://www.spin.com/2013/03/dave-sitek-federal-prism-2013-release-schedule/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/49847-tv-on-the-radios-dave-siteks-federal-prism-label-to-release-new-music-from-tvotr-scarlett-johansson-kelis-freddie-gibbs-more/ |title=TV on the Radio's Dave Sitek's Federal Prism Label to Release New Music From TVOTR, Scarlett Johansson, Kelis, Freddie Gibbs, More &#124; News |website=Pitchfork |date=March 11, 2013 |access-date=April 23, 2014 |archive-date=March 26, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326033856/http://pitchfork.com/news/49847-tv-on-the-radios-dave-siteks-federal-prism-label-to-release-new-music-from-tvotr-scarlett-johansson-kelis-freddie-gibbs-more/ |url-status=live }}</ref> A new single, "Jerk Ribs", subsequently premiered online.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.spin.com/2013/04/kelis-jerk-ribs-stream-dave-sitek-federal-prism/ |title=Stream Kelis' Clattering 'Jerk Ribs,' Produced by Dave Sitek &#124; SPIN &#124; Songs |publisher=SPIN |date=April 23, 2013 |access-date=April 23, 2014 |archive-date=November 5, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105232654/http://www.spin.com/2013/04/kelis-jerk-ribs-stream-dave-sitek-federal-prism/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Kelis then signed to British independent label [[Ninja Tune]] for the release of the album, titled ''[[Food (Kelis album)|Food]]'', in 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pitchfork.com/news/53309-kelis-details-dave-sitek-produced-new-album-food-signs-to-ninja-tune/ |title=Kelis Details Dave Sitek-Produced New Album Food, Signs to Ninja Tune &#124; News |website=Pitchfork |date=December 11, 2013 |access-date=April 23, 2014 |archive-date=April 20, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140420202529/http://pitchfork.com/news/53309-kelis-details-dave-sitek-produced-new-album-food-signs-to-ninja-tune/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Produced entirely by Sitek, ''Food'' entered the UK Albums Chart at number 20, becoming Kelis' second highest-peaking album after ''Tasty'' in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/paolo-nutini-spends-second-week-on-top-with-caustic-love-2960/ |title=Paolo Nutini spends second week on top with Caustic Love |publisher=Officialcharts.com |date=April 27, 2014 |access-date=July 10, 2014 |archive-date=July 9, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140709083729/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/paolo-nutini-spends-second-week-on-top-with-caustic-love-2960/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In the U.S., it reached number 73 on the ''Billboard'' 200 and the top twenty on the [[Independent Albums]].<ref name=Billboard/> Subsequent singles were "Rumble" (a top 40 hit on the UK Independent Singles Chart) and "Friday Fish Fry".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/independent-singles-chart/20140427/130/ |title=Official Independent Singles Chart Top 50 - 27 April 2014 - 03 May 2014 |access-date=2022-08-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/release/10824686-Kelis-Friday-Fish-Fry-Remixes |title=Kelis – Friday Fish Fry (Remixes) |access-date=2022-08-03}}</ref> ''Food'' received positive reviews from critics, including a five-star review in ''[[The Independent]]'': "Kelis's sixth album is a moveable feast [...] If music be the food of love, Kelis has cooked up something tasty enough to satisfy all but the hungriest of hearts."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/food/kelis/critic-reviews |title=FOOD by Kelis |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref> [[Mic (media company)|Mic]] named ''Food'' the best album of 2014 and of Kelis's career, while ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' listed it as one of the year's best R&B albums.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mic.com/articles/108656/this-was-the-best-album-of-the-year-but-you-won-t-hear-it-at-the-grammys |title=This Was the Best Album of the Year — but You Won’t Hear It at the Grammys |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref>

A limited edition version of ''Food'' included remixes by electronic producers such as [[Actress (musician)|Actress]], [[Mount Kimbie]], [[Ben Pearce]], [[Ben Westbeech|Breach]], [[Machinedrum]], and [[Will Saul]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.complex.com/music/2014/04/kelis-runnin-machinedrum-remix | title=Kelis - "Runnin' (Machinedrum Remix)" | website=[[Complex Networks]] }}</ref> Breach reworked his remix of "Rumble" into a new track featuring Kelis, "The Key", which was released as a single later in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/22506/1/watch-breach-kelis-decade-defying-new-video|title=Watch Breach and Kelis' decade-defying new video|author=Dazed|work=Dazed|date=November 11, 2014|access-date=January 1, 2015|archive-date=January 11, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150111204413/http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/22506/1/watch-breach-kelis-decade-defying-new-video|url-status=live}}</ref> Kelis' performance at London's [[Somerset House]] was recorded and released as an album, ''Live in London'', in late 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/nov/18/kelis-live-in-london-album-stream|title=Kelis: Live in London – album stream|first=Guardian|last=music|work=the Guardian|date=November 18, 2014|access-date=December 12, 2016|archive-date=November 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107033407/https://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/nov/18/kelis-live-in-london-album-stream|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, Kelis featured on veteran disco producer [[Giorgio Moroder]]'s album, ''[[Déjà Vu (Giorgio Moroder album)|Déjà Vu]]'', singing on the track, "Back and Forth".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://diymag.com/2015/04/16/giorgio-moroder-details-deja-vu-his-first-album-in-30-years|title=Giorgio Moroder details 'Déjà Vu', his first album in 30 years|access-date=April 21, 2020|archive-date=November 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201129124139/https://diymag.com/2015/04/16/giorgio-moroder-details-deja-vu-his-first-album-in-30-years|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, she featured alongside rapper [[Sage The Gemini]] on English house DJ [[TCTS]]' single "Do It Like Me (Icy Feet)"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fTpP0ZmfsdM |archive-url=https://ghostarchive.org/varchive/youtube/20211212/fTpP0ZmfsdM| archive-date=2021-12-12 |url-status=live|title=TCTS - Do It Like Me (Icy Feet) [Official Audio] ft. Sage The Gemini, Kelis|website=[[YouTube]]}}{{cbignore}}</ref> and on [[Dan Black]]'s single "Farewell". Also in 2017, she released a new song, "[[Who's Lovin' You]]" (originally sung by [[The Miracles]]), on the [[Danger Mouse (musician)|Danger Mouse]]-produced compilation, ''Resistance Radio: The Man in The High Castle'', for the television show ''[[The Man in the High Castle (TV series)|The Man in the High Castle]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CaUpVjKUqaM|title=Kelis - Who's Lovin' You (Audio)|publisher=[[YouTube]]|access-date=September 2, 2017|archive-date=April 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415015615/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CaUpVjKUqaM|url-status=live}}</ref>

===2018–present: ''Kaleidoscope'' anniversary tour and new music===
Kelis contributed vocals to the dance track "My Milkshake", a rework of her 2003 single "Milkshake" by British producer Freejak, in 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.wonderlandmagazine.com/2018/07/06/premiere-kelis-x-freejak-milkshake/ | title=Premiere: Kelis x Freejak - "My Milkshake" &#124; Wonderland Magazine | date=July 6, 2018 }}</ref> Kelis embarked on the ''Kaleidoscope'' 20th Anniversary Tour, a UK and European tour celebrating the 20th-anniversary release of her debut album ''Kaleidoscope'', in March 2020, though this was cut short due to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kelis-announces-kaleidoscope-20th-anniversary-tour/|title=Kelis Announces Kaleidoscope 20th Anniversary Tour|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Strauss|first=Matthew|date=November 18, 2019|access-date=November 23, 2019|archive-date=November 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123073306/https://pitchfork.com/news/kelis-announces-kaleidoscope-20th-anniversary-tour/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/49145/1/kelis-shares-her-favourite-lockdown-recipes-cooked-cannabis-netflix |title=Kelis shares her favourite lockdown recipes |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref> Kelis was featured on a [[Disclosure (band)|Disclosure]] song titled "Watch Your Step" in 2020 and on "Deal with It", a track on the debut mixtape by [[Ashnikko]], ''[[Demidevil]]'', in 2021. The former single, from Disclosure's [[Grammy Award]]-nominated album ''[[Energy (Disclosure album)|Energy]]'', received frequent airplay on [[BBC]] radio stations in the UK and reached the UK dance chart top 40.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://edmmaniac.com/disclosure-releases-special-edition-energy-album2020/ | title=Disclosure Releases Special Edition 'Energy' Album | date=December 18, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/dance-singles-chart/20200911/104/ |title=Official Dance Singles Chart Top 40 - 11 September 2020 - 17 September 2020 |access-date=2022-08-04}}</ref> In October 2020, a biographical animated short about her life as a singer and chef was released on YouTube.{{citation needed|date=August 2022}}

Kelis revealed to ''[[i-D]]'' magazine in 2019 that she was working on an EP that, at the time of the interview, was intended for release in 2020;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/pa7nyk/kelis-interview-kaleidoscope-pharrell-nerd-2019|title=Kelis on 20 Years of Staying Ahead of the Game|work=[[i-D]]|last=Horrowitz|first=Stephen J.|date=November 22, 2019|access-date=November 23, 2019|archive-date=November 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123073306/https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/pa7nyk/kelis-interview-kaleidoscope-pharrell-nerd-2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in 2021, she said an album, ''Dirt'', would be released in 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toyazworldblog.net/2021/12/kelis-announces-new-album-dirt.html|title=Kelis announces new album "Dirt"|access-date=January 11, 2022|archive-date=January 11, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220111102335/https://www.toyazworldblog.net/2021/12/kelis-announces-new-album-dirt.html|url-status=live}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=August 2022}} Kelis released the single "Midnight Snacks" in 2021 and "Feed Them" in 2022, the latter in collaboration with the meal delivery service Daily Harvest.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/culture/product-recommendations/kelis-feed-them-daily-harvest-campaign-1235060913/|title=Kelis Shares a Meaningful Message in New Song 'Feed Them' in a Collab With Daily Harvest|magazine=Billboard|last=Muhammad|first=Latifah|date=April 19, 2022|access-date=May 5, 2022|archive-date=May 5, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220505151444/https://www.billboard.com/culture/product-recommendations/kelis-feed-them-daily-harvest-campaign-1235060913/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/kelis-announces-new-single-midnight-snacks__34116/|title=Kelis announces new single Midnight Snacks|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=September 27, 2021|access-date=September 29, 2021|archive-date=September 28, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210928141942/https://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/kelis-announces-new-single-midnight-snacks__34116/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vibe.com/music/music-news/kelis-new-single-midnight-snacks-giveaway-1234630872/|title=Kelis Has Tasty Treat For Fans Who Pre-Save Her New Single, "Midnight Snacks"|website=Vibe|last=Abraham|first=Mya|date=October 6, 2021|access-date=October 8, 2021|archive-date=October 8, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211008104405/https://www.vibe.com/music/music-news/kelis-new-single-midnight-snacks-giveaway-1234630872/|url-status=live}}</ref>

An interpolation of Kelis's "Milkshake" was used in the [[Beyoncé]] song "Energy", on her 2022 album ''[[Renaissance (Beyoncé album)|Renaissance]]''. The song was updated on some streaming services to remove the interpolation after Kelis said that she was not notified nor asked for approval for the song's use. Kelis said that Pharrell Williams and Chad Hugo of the Neptunes, the credited songwriters on "Milkshake", had "stolen" and "swindled" her publishing rights for the song.<ref>{{cite web|first=Cheyenne |last=Roundtree |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/beyonce-removes-kelis-milkshake-energy-1390926/ |title=Beyoncé Removes 'Milkshake' From 'Energy' After Kelis Called Her Out |work=Rolling Stone |date=2016-11-04 |accessdate=2022-08-03}}</ref>

==Other ventures==
===Culinary===
Between 2006 and 2010, Kelis trained part-time as a [[saucier]], eventually graduating from [[Le Cordon Bleu]] culinary school.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Dingwall |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/music-news/2010/05/13/r-b-star-kelis-i-almost-quit-music-to-become-a-chef-86908-22254921/ |title=R&B star Kelis: I almost quit music to become a chef |newspaper=Daily Record |date=May 13, 2010 |access-date=December 14, 2012 |archive-date=August 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815002148/http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/music-news/2010/05/13/r-b-star-kelis-i-almost-quit-music-to-become-a-chef-86908-22254921/ |url-status=live }}</ref> 
In 2013, Kelis debuted her sauce line, Feast, at the Beverly Hills Food & Wine Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/2013/11/kelis-debuts-new-sauce-line-feast/|title=Kelis Debuts New Sauce Line 'Feast'|date=November 20, 2013|access-date=July 15, 2015|archive-date=July 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716131005/http://www.vibe.com/2013/11/kelis-debuts-new-sauce-line-feast/|url-status=live}}</ref> Kelis has described sauce as "what accessories are to a woman's outfit. Sauce defines where the dish is from and who's making it [...] I think everything is better smothered, poured, or dipped."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://firstwefeast.com/eat/kelis-talks-culinary-school-and-jerk-ribs-reveals-what-dish-brings-grown-men-to-the-yard/|title=Kelis Talks Culinary School and Jerk Ribs, Reveals What Dish Brings Grown Men to the Yard|access-date=July 15, 2015|archive-date=July 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716052454/http://firstwefeast.com/eat/kelis-talks-culinary-school-and-jerk-ribs-reveals-what-dish-brings-grown-men-to-the-yard/|url-status=live}}</ref> The line went on general sale in 2015 under the new name of Bounty & Full.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soulbounce.com/2015/02/kelis-gets-ready-to-launch-new-line-of-sauces-bounty-full/|title=Kelis Gets Ready To Launch New Line Of Sauces, 'Bounty & Full'|website=Soulbounce.com|date=February 20, 2015|language=en-US|access-date=April 20, 2019|archive-date=April 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420193156/http://www.soulbounce.com/2015/02/kelis-gets-ready-to-launch-new-line-of-sauces-bounty-full/|url-status=live}}</ref> Kelis's first [[cookbook]], ''My Life on a Plate'', was released in 2015; Kelis describes it as "an exploration of tastes and cultures, and my experience as a chef, musician, mother and wife".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/60387-kelis-announces-cookbook-my-life-on-a-plate/|title=Kelis Announces Cookbook My Life on a Plate - Pitchfork|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=July 14, 2015|access-date=April 21, 2020|archive-date=December 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191223192138/https://pitchfork.com/news/60387-kelis-announces-cookbook-my-life-on-a-plate/|url-status=live}}</ref> Kelis had previously written an unreleased cookbook with Lauren Pesavento in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/news/news_headlines/2006/03/kelis_talks_cookbook_new_album_and_nas_ex_carmen/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20090429033214/http://www.vibe.com/news/news_headlines/2006/03/kelis_talks_cookbook_new_album_and_nas_ex_carmen/|archive-date= April 29, 2009|title= Kelis Talks Cookbook, New Album and Nas' Ex Carmen|last= Lelinwalla|first= Mark |date= March 14, 2006|publisher= vibe.com|access-date=May 22, 2009}}</ref>

In 2014, Kelis set up a food truck to cook for attendees of the American music festival [[SXSW]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essence.com/2014/03/14/photo-fab-kelis-sets-food-truck-sxsw|title=Photo Fab: Kelis Sets Up a Food Truck at SXSW|work=Essence|date=March 14, 2014|access-date=July 15, 2015|archive-date=July 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716111600/http://www.essence.com/2014/03/14/photo-fab-kelis-sets-food-truck-sxsw|url-status=live}}</ref> She promoted her 2014 album ''Food'' by sharing her recipes for apple farro, jerk ribs, New York vanilla bean cheesecake, and more on the [[Spotify]] app [[Supper (Spotify)|Supper]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Ulloa|first=Nina|title=Did You Know Kelis is a Trained Chef? Learn Her Recipes and Hear Her Playlists…|url=http://www.digitalmusicnews.com/permalink/2014/04/15/kelissupper|publisher=Digital Music News|date=April 15, 2014|access-date=June 8, 2019|archive-date=May 6, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506145310/http://www.digitalmusicnews.com/permalink/2014/04/15/kelissupper|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, Kelis and cooking duo Le Bun opened a pop-up restaurant in London that she subsequently adapted as a food truck to tour around UK music festivals.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/jul/04/singer-turned-chef-kelis-pops-up-london-restaurant | title=Singer-turned-chef Kelis pops up in London restaurant | website=[[TheGuardian.com]] | date=July 4, 2016 }}</ref> In 2017, she released a [[milkshake]] recipe in collaboration with [[Baileys]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2017/09/171278/kelis-milkshakes-song-recipe-secret | title=Kelis Finally Revealed Why Her "Milkshake" Brings All the Boys to the Yard }}</ref> In 2019, Kelis developed an exclusive menu with a local street food vendor for Jam on Rye Festival in London.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://thefestivals.uk/jam-on-rye-kelis-food/ | title=Kelis to partner with Only Jerkin' and serve new menu at Jam on Rye | date=May 2, 2019 }}</ref>

In 2014, the [[Cooking Channel]] aired a cooking TV series starring Kelis, called ''Saucy and Sweet''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/03/watch-the-first-episode-of-kelis-new-cooking-show-saucy-and-sweet/|title=Watch the first episode of Kelis' new cooking show, Saucy and Sweet|date=March 1, 2014|access-date=July 15, 2015|archive-date=July 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150716115345/http://consequenceofsound.net/2014/03/watch-the-first-episode-of-kelis-new-cooking-show-saucy-and-sweet/|url-status=live}}</ref> Kelis appears in ''[[Cooked with Cannabis]]'', a competition [[Cooking show|cooking series]] that [[Netflix]] launched on [[420 (cannabis culture)|April 20, 2020]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/kelis-announces-new-cannabis-themed-netflix-cooking-show/|title=Kelis Announces New Cannabis-Themed Netflix Cooking Show|website=Pitchfork|date=March 19, 2020|language=en|access-date=March 19, 2020|archive-date=March 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319192156/https://pitchfork.com/news/kelis-announces-new-cannabis-themed-netflix-cooking-show/|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Fashion/TV===
In 2006, Kelis designed her own line of fashion accessories, called Cake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1541682/20060925/kelis.jhtml|title=Kelis Wants To Help You Dress, Cook – But She Won't Do Your Taxes|last=Rodriguez|first=Jayson|date=September 25, 2006|work=mtv|access-date=May 22, 2009|archive-date=April 3, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070403235352/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1541682/20060925/kelis.jhtml|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2007, she was in talks to host a ''[[Project Runway]]''-esque show for [[VH1]] and auditioned for various film and TV roles.<ref name="billboard-oct07"/><ref name="ew-oct07">{{cite magazine |url=http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2007/10/jive-records-dr.html |title=Jive Records drops Kelis |access-date=October 28, 2007 |last=Halperin |first=Shirley |magazine=Entertainment Weekly |date=October 26, 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028235125/http://hollywoodinsider.ew.com/2007/10/jive-records-dr.html |archive-date=October 28, 2007  }}</ref>

In 2017, Kelis joined [[BBC One]]'s singing contest ''[[Pitch Battle]]'' as a judge of the competition alongside [[Gareth Malone]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Behind the scenes at Pitch Battle|language=en-GB|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/entertainment-arts-40258771|access-date=August 10, 2020|archive-date=May 6, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506145309/https://www.bbc.com/news/av/entertainment-arts-40258771|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2020, Kelis competed as the Daisy in the British version of ''[[The Masked Singer (British TV series)|The Masked Singer]]'', where she was eliminated in the fifth episode.<ref>[https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1234370/the-masked-daisy-kelis-backstage-ban-celebrities-identities-itv-video The Masked Singer (UK) Kelis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131042515/https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1234370/the-masked-daisy-kelis-backstage-ban-celebrities-identities-itv-video |date=January 31, 2020 }} by Charlotte McIntyre, Daily Express, January 28, 2020.</ref>

==Personal life==
Kelis met rapper [[Nas]] at an [[MTV Video Music Awards]] party in 2002; they dated for one year before becoming engaged in 2004, and marrying in January 2005. In April 2009, she filed for divorce, citing [[irreconcilable differences]]. She was seven months pregnant at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/milkshake-singer-kelis-files-for-divorce/?xid=rss-topheadlines|title='Milkshake' Singer Kelis Files for Divorce|date=April 30, 2009|work=People|access-date=May 6, 2022|archive-date=January 23, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210123121838/https://people.com/celebrity/milkshake-singer-kelis-files-for-divorce/?xid=rss-topheadlines|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2009, Kelis gave birth to her first son, Knight.<ref>{{cite web|date=July 22, 2009|title=Kelis Welcomes a Baby Boy!|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/news/kelis-gives-birth-to-baby-boy-2009227|work=Us Weekly|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090723195637/http://www.usmagazine.com/news/kelis-gives-birth-to-baby-boy-2009227|archive-date=July 23, 2009}}</ref> The couple's divorce was finalized in May 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmz.com/2010/05/24/nas-kelis-divorced/|title=Nas & Kelis – Officially divorced|publisher=Tmz.com|access-date=December 14, 2012|archive-date=December 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121205070633/http://www.tmz.com/2010/05/24/nas-kelis-divorced|url-status=live}}</ref> Kelis has described her relationship with Nas as physically and mentally abusive, crediting the anticipated birth of her child as a factor in her decision to end her marriage.<ref name=":1">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/kelis-nas-marriage-domestic-abuse-rapper-rihanna-divorce-kanye-west-a8325006.html|title=Kelis claims Nas abused her during marriage – and Rihanna played a part in their divorce|last=O'Connor|first=Roisin|date=April 27, 2018|website=The Independent|access-date=December 7, 2018|archive-date=December 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209162214/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/kelis-nas-marriage-domestic-abuse-rapper-rihanna-divorce-kanye-west-a8325006.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Kelis also recalled that the [[domestic violence]] incident between [[Rihanna]] and [[Chris Brown]] influenced her decision to leave Nas.<ref name=":1" /> After she saw pictures of Rihanna battered she felt embarrassed because she also had bruises all over her body, but she was hesitant to speak out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehollywoodunlocked.com/hu-exclusive-kelis-breaks-her-silence-on-violent-marriage-and-custody-battle-with-nas/|title=Kelis breaks her silence on violent marriage and custody battle with Nas|last=Johnson|first=Jeroslyn|date=April 26, 2018|website=Hollywood Unlocked|publisher=Hollywood Unlocked|access-date=April 26, 2018|archive-date=April 26, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426204406/http://thehollywoodunlocked.com/hu-exclusive-kelis-breaks-her-silence-on-violent-marriage-and-custody-battle-with-nas/|url-status=live}}</ref> Nas replied to the accusations on social media, accusing Kelis of attempting to [[slander]] him in the time of a custody battle and accusing Kelis of abusing his daughter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thesource.com/2018/09/07/nas-writes-seven-part-series-of-instagram-posts-to-ex-wife-kelis/|title=Nas Writes Seven-Part Series of Instagram Posts to Ex-Wife Kelis|date=September 7, 2018|work=The Source|access-date=November 1, 2018|archive-date=November 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110124004/http://thesource.com/2018/09/07/nas-writes-seven-part-series-of-instagram-posts-to-ex-wife-kelis/|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to the domestic abuse claims, she alleged that Nas' drinking habit began to damage their relationship, and he had been having [[Adultery|adulterous]] affairs for two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2018/04/26/606080885/kelis-nas-ex-wife-accuses-rapper-of-physical-and-mental-abuse|title=Kelis, Nas' Ex-Wife, Accuses Rapper Of Physical And Mental Abuse|last=Carmichael|first=Rodney|date=April 26, 2018|website=NPR|access-date=April 27, 2018|archive-date=April 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427183734/https://www.npr.org/sections/therecord/2018/04/26/606080885/kelis-nas-ex-wife-accuses-rapper-of-physical-and-mental-abuse|url-status=live}}</ref> They are involved in an ongoing custody battle over their son. In April 2018, Kelis claimed that until 2012, she had not seen "a single cent" from Nas in child support and he has not been an active parent. She explained, "He doesn't participate. He shows up when it's fun, he shows up when there's a good photo-op... I don't think it should be 50/50 just because you had sperm involved."<ref>{{cite web|last=Zimmerman|first=Amy|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/kelis-opens-up-about-nas-shocking-alleged-abuse-i-had-bruises-all-over-my-body|title=Kelis Opens Up About Nas's Shocking Alleged Abuse: 'I Had Bruises All Over My Body'|website=[[The Daily Beast]]|date=April 26, 2020|access-date=October 19, 2020|archive-date=September 21, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200921134410/https://www.thedailybeast.com/kelis-opens-up-about-nas-shocking-alleged-abuse-i-had-bruises-all-over-my-body|url-status=live}}</ref>

In March 2007, Kelis was detained by police in [[Miami Beach, Florida]], and charged with disorderly conduct. The arrest report said an operation in which officers posed as prostitutes in the [[South Beach]] nightclub district was disrupted when Kelis started screaming racial profanities at them. She was sent to [[Miami-Dade County]] Jail, and was later released on a $1,500 bond.<ref>{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1054255/kelis-arrested-in-scuffle-with-undercover-police|title=Kelis Arrested In Scuffle With Undercover Police|date=March 2, 2007|magazine=Billboard|access-date=March 23, 2018|archive-date=October 25, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171025101925/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1054255/kelis-arrested-in-scuffle-with-undercover-police|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2008, Kelis was acquitted of the charges. A spokesman for Kelis further commented that the singer would file a lawsuit against the Miami Beach Police, claiming unlawful arrest and the violation of her civil rights.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1594700/20080912/nas.jhtml |title=Kelis Acquitted On Charges Of Disorderly Conduct, Resisting Arrest |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date=September 12, 2008 |access-date=September 13, 2008 |archive-date=September 13, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913064148/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1594700/20080912/nas.jhtml |url-status=live }}</ref>

Kelis married photographer Mike Mora in 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kelis-details-alleged-mental-and-physical-abuse-from-nas/|title=Kelis Claims She Endured 'a Lot of Mental and Physical Abuse' During Nas Marriage|last=Hautman|first=Nicholas|date=April 26, 2018|website=US Weekly|access-date=April 26, 2018|archive-date=April 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427120050/https://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/kelis-details-alleged-mental-and-physical-abuse-from-nas/|url-status=live}}</ref> and she gave birth to her second son Shepherd in November 2015.<ref>{{cite web|date=December 17, 2015|title=Kelis Gives Birth to Her Second Son|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/724683/kelis-gives-birth-to-her-second-son|work=[[E! News]]|access-date=April 28, 2016|archive-date=March 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160330223608/http://www.eonline.com/news/724683/kelis-gives-birth-to-her-second-son|url-status=live}}</ref> Since January 2020, Kelis has been living on a remote farm outside Los Angeles that she manages, when not performing around the world.<ref>{{cite web |last=Freeman |first=Hadley |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/jan/30/unmasked-singer-kelis-on-music-men-and-her-missing-money |title=Unmasked singer: Kelis on music, men and her missing money |work=The Guardian |date=January 30, 2020 |access-date=October 19, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130071646/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/jan/30/unmasked-singer-kelis-on-music-men-and-her-missing-money |archive-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> In September 2020, she gave birth to a daughter named Galilee, her second child with Mora and her third overall.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Peters |first=Mitchell |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9448177/kelis-gives-birth-baby-girl-announcement |title=Kelis Welcomes First Daughter Following 'Intense' Labor |magazine=Billboard |date=September 13, 2020 |access-date=October 19, 2020 |archive-date=September 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200917120659/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9448177/kelis-gives-birth-baby-girl-announcement |url-status=live }}</ref> In September 2021, Mora revealed publicly that he was battling stage-4 stomach cancer. In an Instagram post, he stated he had been diagnosed with advanced [[stomach cancer|gastric adenocarcinoma]] in September 2020 and given eighteen months to live.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://urbanislandz.com/2021/10/08/kelis-drops-comeback-single-midnight-snacks-as-husband-battles-terminal-cancel/|title=Kelis Drops Comeback Single 'Midnight Snacks' As Husband Battles Terminal Cancer|last=Litton|first=Jamie|website=Urban Islandz|date=October 8, 2021|access-date=October 15, 2021|archive-date=October 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211015201921/https://urbanislandz.com/2021/10/08/kelis-drops-comeback-single-midnight-snacks-as-husband-battles-terminal-cancel/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/kelis-husband-reveals-doctors-can-no-nothing-more-him-amid-cancer-battle-1639400|title=Kelis' Husband Reveals Doctors Can Do Nothing More for Him Amid Cancer Battle|last=Smith|first=Ryan|work=[[Newsweek]]|date=October 15, 2021|access-date=October 15, 2021|archive-date=October 15, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211015160800/https://www.newsweek.com/kelis-husband-reveals-doctors-can-no-nothing-more-him-amid-cancer-battle-1639400|url-status=live}}</ref> Mora died on March 14, 2022, at age 37.<ref>{{cite web |last=Uwumarogie |first=Victoria |url=https://www.essence.com/celebrity/kelis-husband-cancer/ |title=Kelis' Husband Mike Mora Passes Away After Battle With Stomach Cancer |work=Essence |date=March 14, 2022 |access-date=March 15, 2022 |archive-date=March 15, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220315043035/https://www.essence.com/celebrity/kelis-husband-cancer/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Khalifeh |first=Mona |url=https://www.etonline.com/mike-mora-singer-kelis-husband-dead-at-37-after-battle-with-cancer-180846 |title=Mike Mora, Singer Kelis' Husband, Dead at 37 After Battle With Cancer |work=[[Entertainment Tonight]] |date=March 14, 2022 |access-date=March 15, 2022 |archive-date=March 15, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220315035013/https://www.etonline.com/mike-mora-singer-kelis-husband-dead-at-37-after-battle-with-cancer-180846 |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Artistry==
[[AXS (company)|AXS]] called Kelis a "punky, rebellious" singer-songwriter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.axs.com/the-10-best-kelis-songs-30917|title=The 10 best Kelis songs|work=AXS|access-date=April 15, 2019|language=en-US|archive-date=May 4, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504145920/http://www.axs.com/the-10-best-kelis-songs-30917|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' considered Kelis's vocals "dynamic" and commended her for being "well schooled in the intricacies of heartache".<ref name="nytimes"/> [[IGN]] described Kelis as  being "[[wikt:strange|strange]], [[wikt:weird|weird]], and [[wikt:eccentric|eccentric]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2004/02/21/kelis-interview|title=Kelis Interview|last=D|first=Spence|date=February 20, 2004|website=IGN|language=en-US|access-date=April 15, 2019|archive-date=April 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415222652/https://www.ign.com/articles/2004/02/21/kelis-interview|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' stated that Kelis made the most of "a voice that lives in the basement".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-xpm-2014-06-10-chi-kelis-concert-review-20140609-story.html|title=Concert review: Kelis at Park West|last=Kot|first=Greg|website=chicagotribune.com|language=en-US|access-date=April 15, 2019|archive-date=April 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415222653/https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/ct-xpm-2014-06-10-chi-kelis-concert-review-20140609-story.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Kelis's debut album ''[[Kaleidoscope (Kelis album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' took influence from a variety of 1970s genres,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/aug/22/artsfeatures.popandrock|title=Kelis, Astoria, London|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=August 22, 2001|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 16, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=April 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416004941/https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2001/aug/22/artsfeatures.popandrock|url-status=live}}</ref> which included [[urban music|urban]], [[rock music|rock]], [[jazz]], [[hip hop music|hip hop]], [[contemporary R&B|R&B]], [[soul music|soul]], and [[disco]] music.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2014/04/spin-interview-kelis/|title=The SPIN Interview: Kelis Talks 'Milkshake,' Feminism, and Inspirational Love|date=April 28, 2014|website=Spin|access-date=April 16, 2019|archive-date=April 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416004936/https://www.spin.com/2014/04/spin-interview-kelis/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/b3wx/|title=BBC - Music - Review of Kelis - Kaleidoscope|last=Easlea|first=Daryl|website=Bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=April 16, 2019|archive-date=January 31, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190131172913/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/b3wx/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pauseandplay.com/looking-through-kelis-kaleidoscope-of-music/|title=Looking through Kelis' 'Kaleidoscope' of music {{!}} Pause & Play CD and Music Site|date=February 27, 2000|website=Pause & Play|language=en-US|access-date=April 16, 2019|archive-date=April 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416004939/https://www.pauseandplay.com/looking-through-kelis-kaleidoscope-of-music/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/1999/11/26/kelis-all-you-need-hate/|title=Kelis: All You Need Is Hate|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2019|archive-date=April 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416004936/https://ew.com/article/1999/11/26/kelis-all-you-need-hate/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/11/17/kelis-kaleidoscope-shae-haley-nerd-interview|title=N.E.R.D.'s Shae Haley on Kaleidoscope, the Kelis album that started it all|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=April 16, 2019|archive-date=April 16, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416004940/https://www.thefader.com/2017/11/17/kelis-kaleidoscope-shae-haley-nerd-interview|url-status=live}}</ref> Kelis cited early [[Sarah Vaughan]], [[Ella Fitzgerald]] and [[Dinah Washington]] as major influences for the album.<ref name="nytimes">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/08/19/magazine/uptown-girl.html|title=Uptown, girl!|last=Chambers|first=Veronica|date=August 19, 2001|work=The New York Times|access-date=April 15, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-date=April 15, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415222811/https://www.nytimes.com/2001/08/19/magazine/uptown-girl.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Several of the album's tracks were designed for clubs, and contained electro beats meant for dancing.<ref name="tasty">{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/4566-tasty/|title=Kelis: Tasty Album Review|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2019|archive-date=April 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420191415/https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/4566-tasty/|url-status=live}}</ref> Her second studio album ''[[Wanderland]]'' resembles musically its predecessor while exploring more modern funk sounds, dabbling heavily into genres such as [[soul music|soul]] and [[hip hop music|rap]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2001/oct/19/shopping.artsfeatures2|title=CD review: Kelis: Wanderland|last=Petridis|first=Alexis|date=October 19, 2001|work=The Guardian|access-date=April 20, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=March 3, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303001458/http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2001/oct/19/shopping.artsfeatures2|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="nme">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/reviews-nme-5756|title=Kelis : Wanderland|last=nme|website=NME|date=September 12, 2005|language=en-US|access-date=April 20, 2019|archive-date=April 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420192833/https://www.nme.com/reviews/album/reviews-nme-5756|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2017/11/14/kelis-wanderland-the-making-of-interview-andrew-coleman|title=This is what it was like to record Wanderland, Kelis's long lost masterpiece|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=April 20, 2019|archive-date=April 20, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190420192829/https://www.thefader.com/2017/11/14/kelis-wanderland-the-making-of-interview-andrew-coleman|url-status=live}}</ref> It carried on the same themes developed in ''Kaleidoscope'', and was criticized for doing so.<ref name="slant">{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/kelis-wanderland/|title=Review: Kelis, Wanderland|last=Cinquemani|first=Sal|website=[[Slant Magazine]]|date=February 22, 2002|language=en-US|access-date=April 20, 2019|archive-date=August 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200803113749/https://www.slantmagazine.com/music/kelis-wanderland/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Kelis's sixth album, ''Food'' (2014), contains influences of [[soul music|soul]], [[funk]], [[gospel music|gospel]], and [[Afrobeat]]&mdash;Kelis said of the album, "You know, those records in your life that your parents played and they resonate with who you are? They make you nostalgic. I wanted to find out how to get that feeling."<ref name=guardian-mar14>{{cite news |first=Kate |last=Hutchinson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/mar/01/kelis-food-david-sitek-ninja-tune |title=Kelis: from dance diva to soul queen and qualified cook &#124; Music |newspaper=The Guardian |access-date=April 23, 2014 |archive-date=April 17, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417104515/http://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/mar/01/kelis-food-david-sitek-ninja-tune |url-status=live }}</ref>

